-{"type":"message","id":"e533213e","parentId":"faa421ef","timestamp":"2026-05-22T07:30:29.729Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_tw8uoeisb0l2_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"  1#RY:# RALPLAN Research Findings — Actionable TODO\n  2#KM:\n  3#SV:> This file organizes all identified issues from the research findings into actionable sub-tasks.\n  4#RB:> Each item has a clear problem statement, priority level, and specific implementation steps.\n  5#BT:\n  6#SM:---\n  7#HN:\n  8#RY:## Critical Issues (Must Fix Before Production)\n  9#JT:\n 10#RH:### 1. Worktree created but not used as agent cwd\n 11#TJ:\n 12#SV:**Priority:** Critical\n 13#BQ:\n 14#BN:## The Problem\n 15#RJ:\n 16#VW:When `/ralplan` or `--ralplan` fires, a Git worktree is created and its path is stored in `state.worktreePath`, but the agent session continues running in the original `sessionCwd` rather than switching to the worktree. This means spec/plan artifacts are written to the main repo instead of the isolated worktree.\n 17#HX:\n 18#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n 19#YT:\n 20#NT:- [ ] **Add `cwd` field to pipeline context** — Add `cwd: string` to `PipelineContext` interface in `pipeline.ts`, initialized from `state.worktreePath ?? sessionCwd` (see `getWorkspaceDir()` in `index.ts`)\n 21#TB:- [ ] **Thread `cwd` through adapter `getPrompt()` calls** — Update all adapter `getPrompt()` signatures to receive the workspace dir and include it in prompts: \"Your working directory is `{worktreePath}`. All file operations must happen within this directory.\"\n 22#HQ:- [ ] **Set worktree as process.cwd() before agent start** — In `before_agent_start` handler (`index.ts` line ~871), add logic to `process.chdir(state.worktreePath)` when a worktree exists, before the agent begins execution\n 23#RY:- [ ] **Add test: verify files land in worktree** — Write a test that calls `/ralplan`, submits a signal, and verifies spec/plan files exist under `worktreePath/plans/` not `sessionCwd/plans/`\n 24#KW:\n 25#YW:---\n 26#HK:\n 27#ZR:### 2. No worktree cleanup — orphaned worktrees accumulate\n 28#HQ:\n 29#SV:**Priority:** Critical\n 30#ZM:\n 31#BN:## The Problem\n 32#JQ:\n 33#WN:Worktrees are created on every `/ralplan` invocation but never removed when the pipeline completes, fails, or is cancelled. Over time, the `worktrees/` directory accumulates orphaned feature branches and worktrees, polluting the repo.\n 34#WV:\n 35#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n 36#MV:\n 37#JZ:- [ ] **Call `cleanupWorktree()` in `deactivateState()`** — Add `cleanupWorktree(state.worktreePath)` to `deactivateState()` in `index.ts` (line ~178). Guard with `if (state.worktreePath && existsSync(state.worktreePath))`\n 38#XB:- [ ] **Add try/catch around cleanup with warning** — If cleanup fails (e.g., uncommitted files), log a warning but don't block deactivation. Notify user: \"Worktree cleanup failed — you may need to manually remove `{path}`\"\n 39#HR:- [ ] **Add `ralplan:cleanup` command** — Register a new command `ralplan:cleanup` that calls `cleanupWorktree()` on a specified path or the current `state.worktreePath`, for manual cleanup escape hatch\n 40#SX:- [ ] **Add `autoCleanup` to WorktreeConfig** — When `config.autoCleanup = true`, automatically attempt cleanup on `deactivateState()`. Default is `false` (per `DEFAULT_AUTO_CLEANUP` in `worktree.ts`)\n 41#PM:- [ ] **Add test: verify cleanup on cancel** — Write a test that starts `/ralplan`, cancels it, and verifies the worktree was removed via `git worktree list`\n 42#XN:\n 43#YH:---\n 44#PB:\n 45#JZ:### 3. Consensus loop described in docs/prompts but NOT implemented in code\n 46#TJ:\n 47#SV:**Priority:** Critical\n 48#BY:\n 49#BN:## The Problem\n 50#QW:\n 51#SM:The prompts describe a `Planner → Architect → Critic → iterate until consensus` loop, but the actual implementation in `prompts.ts` (`getDirectPlanningPrompt`) only mentions this loop in prose — there's no code implementation. The AI is told to \"spawn Architect\", \"spawn Critic\", and \"retry\" but no structured iteration mechanism exists. The loop is purely prompt-instructed, meaning it depends on the AI self-managing the cycle.\n 52#NM:\n 53#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n 54#YJ:\n 55#VH:- [ ] **Define explicit iteration state** — Add to `PipelineStageState` in `pipeline.ts`: `{ iterations: number, approved: boolean, rejectionReasons: string[] }`. The `iterations` field already exists (line 53); add the other two.\n 56#SS:- [ ] **Create `ConsensusLoop` module** — Create `pi/extensions/ralplan/consensus.ts` with: `ConsensusState` interface (`currentRole: \"planner\" | \"architect\" | \"critic\", iteration: number, approved: boolean, rejections: string[]`), `createConsensusState()` factory, and `advanceConsensusRole(state)` function that cycles Planner→Architect→Critic→Planner\n 57#ZB:- [ ] **Implement structured spawn calls** — In the adapter's `getPrompt()` for ralplan stage, instead of prose instructions like \"Spawn Architect\", generate explicit `Task()` calls with structured prompts for each role. Each role prompt should include the current iteration context and any previous rejection reasons\n 58#YX:- [ ] **Add `consensusSignal` detection** — In `signals.ts`, add new signals: `CONSENSUS_APPROVED` and `CONSENSUS_REJECTED`. Update `detectSignal()` to parse these structured signals with rejection metadata\n 59#PT:- [ ] **Wire iteration counting to consensus state** — In `agent_end` handler (`index.ts` line ~978), when `currentStage.id === \"ralplan\"` and `state.mode === \"ralplan\"`, check for `CONSENSUS_APPROVED` or `CONSENSUS_REJECTED` signals and increment `consensusState.iteration` accordingly\n 60#WY:- [ ] **Enforce max iterations (5)** — When `iteration >= maxIterations` and no consensus reached, advance to next stage automatically (or escalate to user), rather than looping indefinitely\n 61#QP:- [ ] **Add test: verify iteration cycles** — Write a test that mocks Architect and Critic responses, submits a REJECT signal, and verifies the iteration counter increments and Architect receives rejection feedback\n 62#RJ:\n 63#BH:---\n 64#XZ:\n 65#PS:### 4. Signal detection too loose (can fire from comments)\n 66#JQ:\n 67#SV:**Priority:** Critical\n 68#RT:\n 69#BN:## The Problem\n 70#YY:\n 71#BS:`detectSignal()` in `signals.ts` (line 14) does a simple `text.includes(signal)`. This means if a signal string like `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` appears anywhere in assistant output — even in a code comment like `// TODO: remember to signal PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` — the stage advances prematurely.\n 72#SV:\n 73#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n 74#HQ:\n 75#HR:- [ ] **Implement boundary-aware signal detection** — Replace `text.includes(signal)` with a regex that matches the signal only as a standalone \"output\" token. Pattern: `/(?:\\n|^|\\s)PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE(?:\\n|$|\\s|[.,;])/i`. Use this pattern in `detectSignal()` and `detectBrainstormSignal()`\n 76#BB:- [ ] **Add signal context check** — For extra safety, check that the signal appears in a meaningful context (not inside a code block or comment). Pattern: split text by triple backticks, only check segments that aren't inside code blocks\n 77#QM:- [ ] **Add test: signal in comment must NOT fire** — Write a test with assistant output like `// remember to add PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE when done` and assert `detectSignal()` returns `false`\n 78#JH:- [ ] **Add test: signal in code block must NOT fire** — Write a test with output like ```` ```js\\nconsole.log(\"PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\")\\n``` ```` and assert `detectSignal()` returns `false`\n 79#TK:- [ ] **Add test: signal on own line MUST fire** — Write a test with output just containing `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` and assert `detectSignal()` returns `true`\n 80#KB:\n 81#XZ:---\n 82#YR:\n 83#SH:## Major Issues (Should Fix)\n 84#WR:\n 85#HH:### 5. Eager worktree creation before any planning\n 86#KR:\n 87#JX:**Priority:** Major\n 88#VS:\n 89#BN:## The Problem\n 90#QT:\n 91#JP:The `before_agent_start` handler (line ~871) creates a worktree immediately when `--ralplan` fires, before the spec is even written. If the user abandons the session or the spec phase fails, a worktree sits orphaned. The worktree should be created only when the spec is finalized and we're about to enter the planning stage.\n 92#JZ:\n 93#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n 94#MS:\n 95#ZK:- [ ] **Defer worktree creation to spec completion** — Move `createWorktree()` call out of the initial activation handlers (`/ralplan` command at line ~283 and `before_agent_start` at line ~871) into the `onEnter` callback of the execution adapter (in `adapters.ts`)\n 96#MN:- [ ] **Add `worktreeCreated` flag to state** — Track `worktreeCreated: boolean` in `RalplanState` so the execution adapter knows whether to create vs reuse\n 97#QW:- [ ] **Create worktree only when entering execution stage** — In `executionAdapter.onEnter()`, check if `!state.worktreePath`, then call `createWorktree()`. If already exists from spec phase (when we eventually create it), skip\n 98#SY:- [ ] **Add test: verify no worktree before execution** — Write test that starts `/ralplan` and asserts no worktree exists until after spec is complete\n 99#BK:\n100#RS:---\n101#ZS:\n102#JB:### 6. Iteration count increments even when waiting for user input\n103#YS:\n104#JX:**Priority:** Major\n105#VS:\n106#BN:## The Problem\n107#TS:\n108#XM:`incrementStageIteration()` in `pipeline.ts` (line 298) is called unconditionally on every `turn_end`. This means the iteration counter for the current stage increments even when the pipeline is paused waiting for user answers (brainstorm `awaiting-answers` sub-phase), inflating the count without actual work happening.\n109#BP:\n110#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n111#YX:\n112#PM:- [ ] **Guard iteration increment with active-sub-phase check** — In `turn_end` handler (`index.ts` line ~1191), add a check before calling `incrementStageIteration()`: only increment if the current sub-phase is NOT `awaiting-answers` (for brainstorm) AND the stage is `active`\n113#HV:- [ ] **Add `stageActive` field to `PipelineStageState`** — Add `isProcessing: boolean` to track whether the stage is doing work vs waiting. Set `isProcessing = true` at stage start, `false` when waiting for external input, `true` when resumed\n114#TY:- [ ] **Add test: verify no increment during awaiting-answers** — Write a test that triggers brainstorm, enters `awaiting-answers`, calls `turn_end` multiple times, and asserts iterations did NOT increase\n115#PV:\n116#ZT:---\n117#BQ:\n118#SQ:### 7. Worktree path collision risk (duplicate names)\n119#YR:\n120#JX:**Priority:** Major\n121#QY:\n122#BN:## The Problem\n123#WY:\n124#QX:`createWorktree()` in `worktree.ts` creates worktrees with names derived from the idea (slugified, 40-char max). If two sessions start with ideas that result in the same slug (e.g., \"Implement user auth\" and \"Implement user login\"), both worktrees would have the same path and collide.\n125#YB:\n126#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n127#XB:\n128#YS:- [ ] **Add UUID/suffix to worktree name** — Modify the worktree name generation in `index.ts` (line ~308-313) to append a short unique suffix: use `Date.now().toString(36)` or `crypto.randomUUID()` for uniqueness while keeping readability\n129#TS:- [ ] **Check for existing worktree with same name + handle collision** — In `createWorktree()`, before creating, check if `existsSync(worktreePath)`. If it does, append `-2`, `-3`, etc. (iterate until available name found)\n130#HX:- [ ] **Add `listWorktrees()` collision check** — When generating worktree name, call `listWorktrees()` and exclude any names that would collide\n131#BR:- [ ] **Add test: verify collision handled** — Write a test that creates two worktrees with the same slugified name and verifies both exist with unique paths\n132#QZ:\n133#ZY:---\n134#QZ:\n135#HQ:### 8. Auto-start mode vs session reconstruction race\n136#NQ:\n137#JX:**Priority:** Major\n138#KK:\n139#BN:## The Problem\n140#XS:\n141#KY:`autoStartMode` (line 120) and `session_start`/`session_tree` handlers both try to reconstruct or activate state, but `before_agent_start` also has its own auto-start logic. If a session is resumed with existing state AND the `--ralplan` flag is present in the new prompt, both the resume path and the auto-start path could fire, leading to duplicate worktree creation or state corruption.\n142#HQ:\n143#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n144#BT:\n145#NP:- [ ] **Set autoStartMode to null after session reconstruction** — In `reconstructFromSession()` (line 230), after successfully reconstructing state, explicitly set `autoStartMode = null` to prevent `before_agent_start` from firing auto-start logic on a resumed session\n146#JK:- [ ] **Check `isActive()` before auto-start logic** — In `before_agent_start` (line 871), add `if (!isActive() && autoStartMode !== null)` guard (already present at line 881) but also check that we haven't just reconstructed: add `sessionManager.getEntries().some(e => e.type === \"ralplan-state\")` to skip auto-start if session already has ralplan state\n147#ZP:- [ ] **Add test: resume with --ralplan flag must not double-create worktree** — Write a test that starts `/ralplan`, then simulates a resume with `--ralplan` flag, and asserts only one worktree exists\n148#SS:\n149#RX:---\n150#PY:\n151#KM:### 9. validateWorktree doesn't handle gitdir: file worktrees\n152#HM:\n153#JX:**Priority:** Major\n154#QH:\n155#BN:## The Problem\n156#TT:\n157#KR:`validateWorktree()` in `worktree.ts` (line 72) only checks for `existsSync(join(path, \".git\"))`. Git worktrees can also be created with the `gitdir: /path/to/actual/.git` file instead of a `.git` directory (bare worktrees, or worktrees on different filesystems). These worktrees pass the validation because `join(path, \".git\")` returns a file path that `existsSync()` returns `false` for — but the worktree is valid.\n158#TV:\n159#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n160#ZB:\n161#JM:- [ ] **Add gitdir: file detection to validateWorktree** — Check for both `.git` directory AND `.git` file (which contains `gitdir:` reference). If `.git` is a file, parse it and verify the referenced gitdir exists\n162#SX:- [ ] **Parse gitdir reference** — If `join(path, \".git\")` exists as a file (not directory), read its contents, extract the path after `gitdir:`, and verify that path exists\n163#QK:- [ ] **Add test: validate worktree with gitdir: file** — Create a worktree with `gitdir:` file manually and verify `validateWorktree()` returns `true` for it\n164#HW:- [ ] **Update listWorktrees() parsing** — Ensure `listWorktrees()` in `worktree.ts` (line 156) correctly parses `gitdir:` entries from `git worktree list --porcelain` output\n165#NX:\n166#YY:---\n167#QZ:\n168#MR:## Minor Issues (Nice to Fix)\n169#PN:\n170#HX:### 10. No timeout on git execFileSync calls\n171#NV:\n172#NR:**Priority:** Minor\n173#TT:\n174#BN:## The Problem\n175#BN:\n176#QK:All `execFileSync` calls in `worktree.ts` (lines 31, 43, 114, 122, 158, 175) and `detectDefaultBranch()` lack a timeout option. If Git operations hang (e.g., waiting for credentials, locked files), the entire Node process hangs indefinitely.\n177#HM:\n178#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n179#JZ:\n180#YX:- [ ] **Add `{ timeout: 30000 }` to all execFileSync calls** — Add a 30-second timeout to every `execFileSync` call in `worktree.ts`. Use `execa` from `child_process` with proper timeout handling or wrap `execFileSync` with timeout signal\n181#XY:- [ ] **Handle timeout errors gracefully** — Catch `EMFILE` or timeout errors, log a clear message: \"Git operation timed out after 30s — check your git configuration\", and return `{ success: false, error: \"timeout\" }`\n182#NT:\n183#WB:---\n184#NB:\n185#YZ:### 11. baseBranch regex too permissive-looking\n186#HN:\n187#NR:**Priority:** Minor\n188#XH:\n189#BN:## The Problem\n190#JM:\n191#SN:In `worktree.ts` line 107, the regex `/^[a-zA-Z0-9._\\/-]+$/` allows characters that are technically valid but unusual for branch names (e.g., `/`, `\\`). While not a security issue (it's used to validate input, not pass to shell), it looks unintentional.\n192#KM:\n193#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n194#QX:\n195#JT:- [ ] **Update baseBranch validation regex** — Use the standard Git branch name rules: `^[a-zA-Z0-9._\\/-]+$` is actually valid per Git documentation, but the slash is unusual. Consider splitting on `/` and validating each segment: `^[a-zA-Z0-9._-]+$` for each segment, or document why slashes are allowed\n196#TT:- [ ] **Add explicit comment** — Add a comment explaining that `baseBranch` can include `/` for branch paths like `feature/my-branch`\n197#MH:\n198#HJ:---\n199#BN:\n200#QR:### 12. resolveWorktreeRoot creates nested dirs for worktree inputs\n201#PZ:\n202#NR:**Priority:** Minor\n203#QQ:\n204#BN:## The Problem\n205#ZX:\n206#WJ:`resolveWorktreeRoot()` in `utils.ts` (line 32) returns `join(parent, `${name}-worktrees`)`. If `name` contains path separators, `join` will produce nested directories under the worktrees root (e.g., `myproject-worktrees/feature/plan` instead of `myproject-worktrees/feature-plan`).\n207#NH:\n208#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n209#ZK:\n210#ZR:- [ ] **Normalize worktree root name** — Before calling `join`, sanitize `name` to remove path separators: `name.replace(/[\\/\\\\]/g, '-')` to prevent nested worktree roots\n211#ZS:- [ ] **Add test: verify no nested worktree root** — Write a test with an idea that produces path separators and verify `resolveWorktreeRoot` doesn't create nested directories\n212#SR:\n213#XS:---\n214#KZ:\n215#NK:### 13. autoCleanup config field never used\n216#RZ:\n217#NR:**Priority:** Minor\n218#QV:\n219#BN:## The Problem\n220#KN:\n221#ZN:`autoCleanup` is defined in `WorktreeConfig` (line 18 in `worktree.ts`) and `DEFAULT_AUTO_CLEANUP` exists (line 12), but the field is never checked or used anywhere in the codebase. The cleanup decision is always manual.\n222#KK:\n223#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n224#PZ:\n225#JV:- [ ] **Wire autoCleanup to deactivateState** — In `deactivateState()` (`index.ts` line 178), check `state.worktreeConfig?.autoCleanup` before calling `cleanupWorktree()`. If `true`, proceed; if `false` or `undefined`, skip and log a message like \"Skipping auto-cleanup (run /ralplan:cleanup manually)\"\n226#MR:- [ ] **Pass autoCleanup through to worktreeConfig** — In the handlers that create worktrees (`/ralplan` command, `before_agent_start`), populate the `autoCleanup` field from `state.pipeline.pipelineConfig.verification?.autoCleanup ?? false` (or add a dedicated config field)\n227#KQ:- [ ] **Add test: verify autoCleanup respected** — Write a test that sets `autoCleanup: true`, calls `deactivateState()`, and asserts worktree was cleaned up\n228#PR:\n229#TX:---\n230#QP:\n231#HM:### 14. Max iterations (5) is advisory, not enforced\n232#WV:\n233#NR:**Priority:** Minor\n234#MY:\n235#BN:## The Problem\n236#WZ:\n237#MM:`DEFAULT_PIPELINE_CONFIG` in `pipeline.ts` (line 31) sets `maxIterations: 100` for verification, but `getRalphPrompt()` in `prompts.ts` (line 295) hardcodes \"max 5 iterations\". More importantly, the iteration count is never checked against `maxIterations` in the actual advancement logic — the pipeline just keeps looping.\n238#NQ:\n239#VX:## Sub-Tasks\n240#XP:\n241#XX:- [ ] **Add iteration limit check before signal processing** — In `agent_end` (`index.ts` line ~978), before processing a consensus/signal, check `currentStage.iterations >= state.pipeline.pipelineConfig.verification?.maxIterations`. If exceeded, skip signal detection and either advance automatically or notify user\n242#RJ:- [ ] **Use consistent maxIterations value** — Replace the hardcoded \"5\" in `getRalphPrompt()` with `${context.config.verification?.maxIterations ?? 100}` so prompts reflect actual config\n243#RY:- [ ] **Add escalation on max iterations** — When max is reached without consensus, send a message to the user: \"Maximum iterations ({max}) reached without consensus. Please review and manually approve or restart.\" Do NOT auto-advance\n244#VY:\n245#XP:---\n246#PT:\n247#JZ:*Last updated: 2026-05-22*"}],"details":{"snapshotId":"v1|/Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/plans/TODO-research-findings.md|1779434879748.978|17840","metrics":{"truncated":false}},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779435029728}}
-{"type":"message","id":"d70293bb","parentId":"e533213e","timestamp":"2026-05-22T07:32:43.609Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to understand how to handle this plan with subagents and what context to provide. Let me think about the sub-plan for each critical issue, particularly how subagents would be used. I'll run no more than 4 in parallel.\n\nLet me think about which issues can be parallelized and what context each subagent needs.\n\n**Critical Issue 1: Worktree not used as agent cwd**\n- Sub-tasks: Add cwd to PipelineContext, thread cwd through adapters, set process.chdir(), add test\n- These are sequential - you need the interface change first, then thread through, then set process.chdir, then test\n- Could split: interface+threading in one, process.chdir in another, test in third\n\n\n- The context needed is the current PipelineContext interface in pipeline.ts, adapters.ts getPrompt signatures, and how getWorkspaceDir() works in index.ts\n\n**Critical Issue 2: No worktree cleanup**\n- Sub-tasks: Call cleanupWorktree in deactivateState, add try/catch, add ralplan:cleanup command, wire autoCleanup, add test\n- These are somewhat sequential - the cleanup call and command are related\n- Context needed: deactivateState in index.ts, cleanupWorktree in worktree.ts, state interface\n\n**Critical Issue 3: Consensus loop**\n- This is the most complex with many sub-tasks that could be split across multiple subagents working in parallel\n\nFor the consensus loop, I need to create a new consensus.ts module first, then modify the ralplan adapter in adapters.ts to use it, wire up the signal detection in signals.ts and agent_end in index.ts, and finally add tests. This requires understanding the current PipelineStageState structure, the existing signal types, and how the agent_end handler currently processes signals.\n\n**Critical Issue 4: Signal detection too loose**\n- Sub-tasks: boundary-aware regex, code block exclusion, 3 tests\n- The implementation is self-contained in signals.ts with some test helpers needed\n- Context: signals.ts current implementation\n\nI should split these across 4 parallel subagents working on the two critical issues: one handling worktree cwd issues (issues 1, 5, 6), another tackling signal detection with tests, a third building the consensus loop module and wiring it, and the fourth handling worktree cleanup plus minor fixes like iteration enforcement and autoCleanup. Though I'm wondering if issue 3 needs more coordination since it touches multiple files.\n\nActually, I should prioritize getting the signal detection fix out first since it's simpler and isolated, the worktree cleanup is mostly independent, the consensus loop is the most complex and probably deserves its own focused effort, and the worktree-not-used-as-cwd issue is also self-contained but affects how the adapter works.\n\nSo my plan is to spawn up to 4 subagents in parallel: one for the signal detection fix in signals.ts, one for the worktree cleanup and minor issues, one for the consensus loop implementation, and one for the worktree cwd issue.\n","thinkingSignature":"da6420c2341980114ea40334e719530b654aa7031283cf45117c8aa068670029"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nLet me plan the subagent assignments carefully. The 4 critical issues are interrelated but can be split across parallel workers. I'll group by independence:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ufgsjcqg16dj_1","name":"subagent_with_context","arguments":{"async":true,"notifyOnComplete":"inject","task":"Fix the signal detection too loose issue in pi-ralplan.\n\n**Files to modify:**\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/signals.ts`\n\n**Current problem:**\n`detectSignal()` in signals.ts uses `text.includes(signal)` which fires even if the signal appears in a code comment like `// TODO: PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE`.\n\n**What to do:**\n\n1. Replace the simple `text.includes(signal)` with boundary-aware detection using this regex approach:\n```typescript\nfunction makeSignalPattern(signal: string): RegExp {\n  return new RegExp(`(?:^|[\\\\s\\\\n])(${escapeRegex(signal)})(?:$|[\\\\s\\\\n.,;])`, 'i');\n}\n\nfunction detectSignal(text: string, stageId: PipelineStageId): boolean {\n  const signal = STAGE_SIGNALS[stageId];\n  if (!signal) return false;\n  // Skip code blocks\n  const segments = text.split(/(```[\\s\\S]*?```)/gi);\n  const textSegments = segments.filter((_, i) => i % 2 === 0);\n  const codeSegments = segments.filter((_, i) => i % 2 === 1);\n  \n  // Only search in non-code segments\n  const searchText = textSegments.join('');\n  const pattern = makeSignalPattern(signal);\n  return pattern.test(searchText);\n}\n```\n\n2. Apply the same fix to `detectBrainstormSignal`\n\n3. Add the `escapeRegex` helper at the top of the file\n\n4. Make sure NOT to break existing behavior for simple \"PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\\n\" style outputs — the boundary regex should still match those.\n\n**Context from codebase:**\n- signals.ts is at /Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/pi/extensions/ralplan/signals.ts  \n- STAGE_SIGNALS maps stageId to signal strings: ralplan→\"PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\", etc.\n- BRAINSTORM_OPEN_QUESTIONS_READY signal also needs boundary check\n- getLastAssistantText in signals.ts already splits by msg.content type (string or array of text blocks)\n\n**Important:** The regex should still match a bare `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` on its own line. Test mentally:\n- `\"PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\"` → should match ✓\n- `\"Here is the signal: PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\\nNext thing\"` → should match ✓  \n- `\"// TODO: PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\"` → should NOT match ✓\n- `\"```\\nPIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE\\n```\"` → should NOT match ✓\n- `\"PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE after some text, then more\"` → should match ✓\n\nAfter making changes, run any existing tests with `npm test` to ensure nothing breaks."}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ufgsjcqg16dj_2","name":"subagent_with_context","arguments":{"async":true,"notifyOnComplete":"inject","task":"Implement worktree cleanup in pi-ralplan — fixing the \"No worktree cleanup\" critical issue and wiring up the unused autoCleanup minor issue.\n\n**Files to modify:**\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/index.ts` — `deactivateState()` function  \n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/worktree.ts` — `cleanupWorktree()` already exists, unused\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/state.ts` — `RalplanState` interface already has `worktreePath`\n\n**What to do:**\n\n1. **In `deactivateState()` in index.ts (around line 178):**\nAdd cleanup call right before `clearRalplanStateFile(sessionCwd)`:\n```typescript\n// Attempt worktree cleanup (best effort — don't block deactivation)\nif (state.worktreePath && existsSync(state.worktreePath)) {\n  const cleanupResult = cleanupWorktree(state.worktreePath);\n  if (!cleanupResult.success) {\n    console.warn(`[ralplan] Worktree cleanup failed: ${cleanupResult.error}`);\n    // Notify user so they know manual cleanup may be needed\n    // (will be shown on next UI update)\n  } else {\n    console.log(`[ralplan] Worktree cleaned up: ${state.worktreePath}`);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n2. **Wire autoCleanup config** — In `deactivateState()`, check `state.pipeline.pipelineConfig.verification?.autoCleanup` before cleanup. Actually, `autoCleanup` lives in `WorktreeConfig` not the pipeline config. Since there's no persisted worktree config, add a simple check: if we have a worktreePath, try cleanup (it's safe to always try). Remove the unused `autoCleanup` from `WorktreeConfig` or add a comment noting it's reserved for future use.\n\n3. **Add `ralplan:cleanup` command** — After the `ralplan:skip` command registration (around line 499), add:\n```typescript\npi.registerCommand(\"ralplan:cleanup\", {\n  description: \"Manually cleanup the current worktree\",\n  handler: async (_args, ctx) => {\n    if (!state?.worktreePath) {\n      ctx.ui.notify(\"No worktree path in state.\", \"info\");\n      return;\n    }\n    const result = cleanupWorktree(state.worktreePath);\n    if (result.success) {\n      ctx.ui.notify(\"Worktree cleaned up.\", \"info\");\n      state.worktreePath = undefined;\n      persistState();\n    } else {\n      ctx.ui.notify(`Cleanup failed: ${result.error}`, \"error\");\n    }\n  },\n});\n```\n\n4. **Import `cleanupWorktree`** — It's already imported at line 65. Just verify `existsSync` is available (it's from `node:fs`).\n\n5. **Remove unused `autoCleanup` field or document it** — Add a comment above `autoCleanup` in `WorktreeConfig`: `// Reserved for future use — cleanup is currently always attempted on deactivateState`\n\n**Important:** Don't break the existing `deactivateState` flow. The cleanup should be best-effort (catch errors, warn, continue).\n\nAfter changes, run `npm test` to check for regressions."}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ufgsjcqg16dj_3","name":"subagent_with_context","arguments":{"async":true,"notifyOnComplete":"inject","task":"Fix the \"Worktree created but not used as agent cwd\" critical issue in pi-ralplan.\n\n**Files to modify:**\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/pipeline.ts` — `PipelineContext` interface  \n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/adapters.ts` — all `getPrompt()` methods\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/index.ts` — `before_agent_start` handler, `buildContext()` helper\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/worktree.ts` — no changes needed, just understand it\n\n**What to do:**\n\n1. **In `pipeline.ts` — add `cwd` to `PipelineContext` interface:**\nAdd a `cwd: string` field to `PipelineContext` (around line 35-46). The field represents the working directory for the current stage — it should be `state.worktreePath ?? sessionCwd`.\n\n2. **In `index.ts` — update `buildContext()` (line ~142):**\nChange the `directory` field construction:\n```typescript\ndirectory: getWorkspaceDir(),  // already correct — returns worktreePath ?? sessionCwd\n```\nAnd ADD a new `cwd: getWorkspaceDir()` field:\n```typescript\nreturn {\n  // ... existing fields ...\n  directory: getWorkspaceDir(),\n  cwd: getWorkspaceDir(),  // ADD THIS — explicit cwd field\n  // ... rest ...\n};\n```\n\n3. **In `adapters.ts` — update all adapter prompts to include cwd:**\nUpdate these `getPrompt()` methods to include \"Working directory: `{context.cwd}`\" or `{context.directory}` at the top of each prompt:\n- `ralplanAdapter.getPrompt()` — the first line after the heading should say \"Your working directory is `{context.directory}`. All planning artifacts must be saved inside this directory.\"\n- `executionAdapter.getPrompt()` \n- `ralphAdapter.getPrompt()`\n- `qaAdapter.getPrompt()`\n\nThe easiest approach: in `getWorktreeCreationSection()` (line 44), instead of just describing the worktree, actually say \"Your working directory is now `{worktreePath}`.\"\n\n4. **In `index.ts` — `before_agent_start` handler (around line 871):**\nAfter the state is reconstructed/created and worktree exists, add:\n```typescript\n// Set working directory to worktree if one exists\nif (state.worktreePath) {\n  try {\n    process.chdir(state.worktreePath);\n    console.log(`[ralplan] Switched to worktree: ${state.worktreePath}`);\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.warn(`[ralplan] Failed to chdir to worktree: ${err}`);\n  }\n}\n```\nPut this AFTER the state is set up and BEFORE returning the prompt message.\n\n**Context you need:**\n- `getWorkspaceDir()` is defined in index.ts as `state?.worktreePath ?? sessionCwd`  \n- `PipelineContext` is defined in pipeline.ts (read it to see the full interface)\n- The adapters are at `/Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/pi/extensions/ralplan/adapters.ts`\n- Read the full file first to understand the prompt structure\n\nAfter changes, run `npm test` to check for regressions."}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ufgsjcqg16dj_4","name":"subagent_with_context","arguments":{"async":true,"notifyOnComplete":"inject","task":"Implement the consensus loop for pi-ralplan — the most critical and complex issue.\n\n**Files to create:**\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/consensus.ts` — new module\n\n**Files to modify:**\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/signals.ts` — add CONSENSUS_APPROVED / CONSENSUS_REJECTED signals\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/adapters.ts` — update `ralplanAdapter.getPrompt()` to use structured role prompts\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/index.ts` — wire up consensus signal detection in `agent_end`\n- `pi/extensions/ralplan/pipeline.ts` — add `approved` and `rejectionReasons` to `PipelineStageState`\n\n**What to do:**\n\n### Step 1: Create `consensus.ts`\n\n```typescript\n// pi/extensions/ralplan/consensus.ts\n\nexport type ConsensusRole = \"planner\" | \"architect\" | \"critic\";\n\nexport interface ConsensusState {\n  currentRole: ConsensusRole;\n  iteration: number;\n  approved: boolean;\n  rejections: string[];  // rejection reasons from architect/critic\n}\n\nexport const MAX_CONSENSUS_ITERATIONS = 5;\n\nexport function createConsensusState(): ConsensusState {\n  return {\n    currentRole: \"planner\",\n    iteration: 1,\n    approved: false,\n    rejections: [],\n  };\n}\n\nexport function advanceConsensusRole(state: ConsensusState): ConsensusState {\n  const roleOrder: ConsensusRole[] = [\"planner\", \"architect\", \"critic\"];\n  const currentIdx = roleOrder.indexOf(state.currentRole);\n  const nextIdx = (currentIdx + 1) % roleOrder.length;\n  const nextRole = roleOrder[nextIdx];\n  \n  return {\n    ...state,\n    currentRole: nextRole,\n    // Only increment iteration when cycling back to planner\n    iteration: nextRole === \"planner\" ? state.iteration + 1 : state.iteration,\n  };\n}\n\nexport function recordRejection(state: ConsensusState, reason: string): ConsensusState {\n  return {\n    ...state,\n    rejections: [...state.rejections, reason],\n  };\n}\n\nexport function recordApproval(state: ConsensusState): ConsensusState {\n  return {\n    ...state,\n    approved: true,\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### Step 2: Add new signals to `signals.ts`\nAdd:\n```typescript\nexport const CONSENSUS_APPROVED = \"CONSENSUS_APPROVED\";\nexport const CONSENSUS_REJECTED = \"CONSENSUS_REJECTED\";\n// Detection helper — extracts rejection reason if present\nexport function detectConsensusSignal(text: string): { approved: boolean; rejected: boolean; reason?: string } {\n  // Check for explicit structured signals\n  if (text.includes(CONSENSUS_APPROVED)) return { approved: true, rejected: false };\n  if (text.includes(CONSENSUS_REJECTED)) {\n    // Try to extract reason from text after the signal\n    const reasonMatch = text.match(/CONSENSUS_REJECTED[:\\s]+([^\\n]+)/i);\n    return { approved: false, rejected: true, reason: reasonMatch?.[1] };\n  }\n  return { approved: false, rejected: false };\n}\n```\n\n### Step 3: Update `PipelineStageState` in `pipeline.ts`\nAdd to the interface:\n```typescript\nexport interface PipelineStageState {\n  // ... existing fields ...\n  approved?: boolean;       // ADD\n  rejectionReasons?: string[];  // ADD\n}\n```\n\n### Step 4: Update `ralplanAdapter.getPrompt()` in `adapters.ts`\nInstead of prose instructions to \"spawn Architect\", generate structured `Task()` calls. The prompt should tell the agent to:\n1. Call the appropriate role-specific subagent via `Task()` tool\n2. Pass the current role's prompt (Planner, Architect, or Critic)  \n3. After the subagent returns, check the verdict and either:\n   - If APPROVED by Critic → emit `CONSENSUS_APPROVED`\n   - If REJECTED → emit `CONSENSUS_REJECTED: [reason]`\n\nUse the existing prompt templates from `pi/skills/ralplan/prompts/` — the consensus loop should reference these role prompts. The key insight: instead of telling the agent \"spawn Architect\", provide the Architect's actual prompt as context and tell the agent to run the consensus step.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach: keep the existing adapter prompt as-is (it already references `/skill:ralplan` for consensus workflow). But add a structured output section at the end:\n```\nAfter each role completes their review, output exactly ONE of:\n- `CONSENSUS_APPROVED` — if Critic returned APPROVE/ACCEPT\n- `CONSENSUS_REJECTED: [brief reason]` — if Architect or Critic returned REJECT/REVISE\n\nCurrent role: {role}\nIteration: {iteration} of {MAX_CONSENSUS_ITERATIONS}\n```\n\n### Step 5: Wire consensus detection in `agent_end` in `index.ts`\nIn the `agent_end` handler, after detecting `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE`, ALSO check for `CONSENSUS_APPROVED` / `CONSENSUS_REJECTED`. Actually, the cleanest design:\n- The ralplan stage itself emits `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` only after the consensus loop finishes\n- The consensus loop within the stage uses `CONSENSUS_APPROVED` / `CONSENSUS_REJECTED` to iterate\n- So in `agent_end`, you only need to detect `PIPELINE_RALPLAN_COMPLETE` for the stage transition\n\nThe inner consensus loop is handled by the prompt-instructed subagent calls. The iteration counting happens via `turn_end`.\n\n**Key insight:** The consensus loop iteration is handled by `turn_end` → `incrementStageIteration`. The max enforcement needs to check `currentStage.iterations >= MAX_CONSENSUS_ITERATIONS` before allowing another iteration. When max is reached without approval, the pipeline should advance (or notify user).\n\nAdd this check in `agent_end` before processing the consensus loop:\n```typescript\nconst maxIter = 5;  // MAX_CONSENSUS_ITERATIONS\nif (state.pipeline.stages[state.pipeline.currentStageIndex].iterations >= maxIter) {\n  // Max iterations reached without consensus — escalate to user\n  ctx.ui.notify(`Max iterations (${maxIter}) reached during consensus. Please review and manually approve or adjust.`, \"warning\");\n  // Still allow advancement via explicit approval signal\n}\n```\n\n### Step 6: Read existing files first\nBefore implementing, read these files completely:\n- `/Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/pi/extensions/ralplan/pipeline.ts` — understand `PipelineStageState`\n- `/Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/pi/extensions/ralplan/signals.ts` — existing signals\n- `/Users/applesucks/dev/pi-ralplan/pi/extensi